{{Infobox building |name = American Surety Building |image = File:100 Broadway IMG 9055.JPG |image_size = 225px |caption = American Surety Building |alternate_names = Bank of Tokyo Building, 100 Broadway |location = 96-100 Broadway, [[Manhattan|New York]], [[New York (state)|NY]] 10005, [[United States]] |coordinates = {{coord|40.7081|-74.0112|display=inline,title|type:landmark_region:US-NY}} |status = Complete |architectural_style = [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] |start_date = 1894 |completion_date = 1896 |opening = |renovation_date = 1920-1922 |building_type = Office |antenna_spire = |height = 338 feet (103 m) |top_floor = |floor_count = 26 |elevator_count = |cost = |floor_area = |architect = [[Bruce Price]] |structural_engineer= |main_contractor = |developer = |owner = Northwood Investors |management = |ren_architect = [[Herman Lee Meader]] |references = }} The '''American Surety Building''' is a historic [[Early skyscrapers|skyscraper]] located at 100 [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], opposite [[Trinity Church, New York|Trinity Church]]. It has been declared a landmark as one of [[Manhattan]]'s most influential early skyscrapers.{{cn|date=July 2017}}
==History== The building was constructed from 1894 to 1896, following designs by noted architect [[Bruce Price]]. It was one of Manhattan's first buildings with steel framing and curtain wall construction. At its original 21 stories, it was Price's first tall building and the second tallest building in New York.{{cn|date=July 2017}}
[[File:Amercian_Surety_Building_1898.jpg|thumb|left|1898 drawing of the American Surety Building.]]In an interview, Price described his design as "a [[campanile]] with four [[pilaster]] faces, the seven flutes being represented by seven rows of windows". The building is set on an irregular, trapezoidal lot, and designed as a [[Neo-Renaissance]] tower clad in Maine granite with a 3-story base, a 12-story shaft, and a 6-story cap. (Its 4th and 15 stories are transitional.) The base is an Ionic entrance [[colonnade]] topped with sculptures in a classical style by [[J. Massey Rhind]]. Above rises a middle section of horizontally banded piers with vertical strips framing the windows, which culminates in a row of figural sculptures extending from the 14th to 15th stories. A further six-story cap (subsequently modified) featured a colonnade of Corinthian pilasters, stone [[cornice]], and a crowning parapet of gilded metal [[acroteria]] on the setback 20th and 21st stories.{{cn|date=July 2017}}
The [[North American Trust Company]] was organized in early 1896, and at the start of 1898, the company was located in the American Surety Building at [[100 Broadway]].<ref name=nyt-trenholm>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=A Place for Colonel Trenholm; Head of North American Trust Company -- W.S. Johnston Succeeds Him in American Surety. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1898/01/20/archives/a-place-for-col-trenholm-head-of-north-american-trust-company-ws.html | work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York City, United States |date= January 20, 1898| page= |access-date=July 16, 2017}}</ref>
In 1920-1922, New York architect [[Herman Lee Meader]] supervised alterations, which included a new L-shaped annex that widened the tower from 7 to 11 bays, and addition of several stories, which greatly modified the original cap.{{cn|date=July 2017}} [[File:American Surety Building.jpg|thumb|100 Broadway entrance in 2007.]]
