{{Infobox NRHP | name = Phipps–McElveen Building | nrhp_type = | image = Phipps-McElveen Building.jpg | caption = | location= 525–529 Penn Avenue ([[Downtown Pittsburgh]]), [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]] | coordinates = {{coord|40|26|34|N|80|0|10|W|region:US-PA_type:edu|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Pittsburgh#Pennsylvania#USA | built = 1896 | architect = | architecture = [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Renaissance Revival]], Early Commercial | added = May 5, 2000 | area = | governing_body = | mpsub = | refnum = 00000451<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> }}
The '''Phipps–McElveen Building''' at 525–529 Penn Avenue in [[Downtown Pittsburgh|downtown]] [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], [[United States|USA]]
==History== The building was built in 1896 by [[Henry Phipps Jr.]], an early business partner of [[Andrew Carnegie]], real estate developer, and philanthropist.
The building served as the location of the McElveen furniture store for about 20 years. By 1919 it was occupied by a clothier, Oppenhiem, Collins & Company, who stayed there until the late 1930s.
Thereafter it was occupied by [[Walgreens]], another furniture store, and a recreation center.<ref name=nom>{{cite web|last=Taylor|first=David L.|title=Phipps–McElveen Building|url={{NRHP-PA|H110781_01H.pdf}}|work=National Register of Historic Places Nomination Form|publisher=Pennsylvania Historical and Museum Commission|accessdate=January 21, 2014|year=1999}}</ref>
The building was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on May 5, 2000.<ref name="nris"/>
